# Interactive Config Architecture

This document describes the implementation architecture for converting our read-only dashboard into a fully dynamic application. We will introduce UI elements for you to input your OpenAI API key, configure advanced scraping options (like connecting to Kiki Login's websocket), and add/delete structural watch targets directly.

## User Review Required

> [!WARNING]
> Please review the data storage approach for the API keys. Because this is a local prototype, we will be saving the `OPENAI_API_KEY` into your local `targetList.json` config file across the server. This makes it effortless to spin up globally without handling `.env` files, but it means your key will be stored securely in plain text within your local project directory. **Do not push your config file to a public GitHub repo!**

## Proposed Changes

---

### Phase 8: The Interactive Settings Layer
We're upgrading the `/settings` page from a read-only table to an active command center.

#### [MODIFY] `src/config/targetList.json` -> Schema Upgrade
- We will expand the schema to hold top-level application configurations:
  - `openaiApiKey: string`
  - `wsEndpoint: string` (For advanced Kiki Login websocket bypass)

#### [MODIFY] `src/app/settings/page.tsx`
- **Global Settings Module**: A new Shadcn `Card` at the top with secure `<Input>` fields to paste your OpenAI Key and your Kiki Login Websocket Endpoint.
- **Dynamic Tables**: We will add a `<form>` mechanism next to each table (Semantic Topics, Creators, Communities) allowing you to type in a new keyword and a priority weight, and push it to the live config.
- **Save State Integration**: All changes will cleanly POST back to our existing `/api/config` headless route.

#### [MODIFY] `src/app/api/synthesize/route.ts`
- Modifying the AI synthesis workflow to dynamically extract the `openaiApiKey` from your live `config.json` file. It will seamlessly check this before defaulting to the mock output block.

#### [MODIFY] `src/lib/scraper/engine.ts` & `trigger/route.ts`
- Altering the scraping orchestration engine. Now, if `wsEndpoint` is defined in your settings UI, the Playwright engine will automatically attempt to dial your anti-detect browser's CDP port instead of spawning its own hidden instance. This guarantees your advanced scraping requirements are respected natively!

